"""
MKT Christ-in-Every-Verse Commentary — Genesis chapters 33–35
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-genesis-33-35.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/genesis.json (verse inventory: ch33=20v, ch34=31v, ch35=29v; total 80)
- data/translation/draft/mediating/genesis.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/genesis.json (existing; merge_comm skips present entries)

Key Christological decisions:
- 33:4 Esau's embrace of Jacob is the direct model for Jesus's parable of the running
  father (Luke 15:20); the running embrace and kiss of the reconciled brother is one
  of the OT's sharpest proleptic images of God's welcome of the returning sinner.
- 33:10 "To see your face is like seeing the face of God" — after Peniel, Jacob sees
  divine forgiveness in the brother's face; the type of Christ as the face of God
  (John 1:18; 2 Cor 4:6: "the light of the knowledge of God's glory displayed in the
  face of Christ"). The face of God revealed in the act of reconciliation.
- 34 (Dinah): no direct NT citation; the chapter is canonically important as the
  revelation of sin's reach into the covenant family and the type of Christ bearing
  sin he did not commit (Isa 53). Simeon and Levi's violence → Jacob's deathbed curse
  (49:5-7) → the priestly tribe cursed but redeemed through Moses/Phinehas. Brief
  canonical-context notes where no direct connection; avoid forced typology.
- 35:18 Benjamin "son of the right hand" — the name given by Jacob to the child born
  from Rachel's death is the type of Christ's exaltation to the right hand of God
  (Ps 110:1; Heb 1:3). Birth through a mother's death and the name "right hand."
- 35:19 Rachel's tomb at Bethlehem — Matt 2:18 / Jer 31:15; the place of Rachel's
  death/weeping is the birthplace of the Messiah, connecting the massacre of the
  innocents to the ancient mourning at Bethlehem.
- 35:10 Jacob renamed Israel (second conferral) — the new name given by God is the
  type of the new name given to believers (Rev 2:17) and of Christ's new exaltation
  name (Phil 2:9).
- 35:22-26 The twelve sons enumerated — the twelve tribes reconstituted in the twelve
  apostles (Matt 10:2-4; 19:28; Rev 21:12-14).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {
"33": {
"1": "<p>Jacob looked up and there was Esau, coming with his four hundred men &#8212; the dreaded meeting Jacob had anticipated since ch32. After the night of wrestling with God at Peniel (32:24&#8211;32), Jacob must face the estranged brother. The wrestling that transformed Jacob prepares him for the encounter with Esau &#8212; the same pattern as the Christian life: the encounter with God in prayer and struggle equips believers for reconciliation with those who have wronged them (Matt 5:23&#8211;24: &#8220;first go and be reconciled to your brother&#8221;). The four hundred men who accompany Esau make the encounter potentially lethal; Jacob&#8217;s approach requires the courage that comes from having met God face to face.</p>",
"2": "<p>He put the female servants and their children in front, Leah and her children next, and Rachel and Joseph in the rear &#8212; Jacob arranges the family in an order that protects the most beloved last. The self-protective instinct that places the least-beloved first is a reminder that even the covenant-bearer&#8217;s love is partial and self-concerned. Christ&#8217;s love for his people is precisely the opposite: &#8220;He himself went ahead&#8221; (v3) &#8212; the shepherd places himself first between the flock and danger (John 10:11: &#8220;The good shepherd lays down his life for the sheep&#8221;). Where Jacob placed the most vulnerable first to protect the most beloved, Christ places himself first to protect the most vulnerable.</p>",
"3": "<p>He himself went on ahead and bowed down to the ground seven times as he approached his brother &#8212; Jacob goes first &#8212; in front of the women and children he had placed behind him &#8212; and bows seven times (the number of completeness). The covenant-bearer&#8217;s prostration before the brother he wronged is the type of Christ&#8217;s kenosis: &#8220;he humbled himself by becoming obedient to death&#8221; (Phil 2:8). The one who has every right to stand upright voluntarily prostrates himself. Seven prostrations &#8212; complete, unreserved humiliation &#8212; is the type of the complete self-emptying of the incarnation: &#8220;he made himself nothing, taking the form of a servant&#8221; (Phil 2:7).</p>",
"4": "<p>But Esau ran to meet Jacob and embraced him; he threw his arms around his neck and kissed him. And they wept &#8212; one of the most emotionally charged reconciliation scenes in the OT, and the direct model for Jesus&#8217;s parable of the prodigal son: &#8220;But while he was still a long way off, his father saw him and was filled with compassion for him; he ran to his son, threw his arms around him and kissed him&#8221; (Luke 15:20). The verbal and gestural parallels are nearly exact: running, throwing the arms around the neck, kissing, weeping. The reconciliation of estranged brothers (Jacob the deceiver received by Esau the wronged) is the type of the divine welcome of the repentant sinner: the God who runs to meet the returning one is the God revealed in Christ. The parable&#8217;s running father is modeled on Esau&#8217;s running embrace &#8212; this is the face of God that Jesus shows.</p>",
"5": "<p>&#8220;Who are these with you?&#8221; Jacob answered, &#8220;They are the children God has graciously given your servant&#8221; &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s attribution of his children to God&#8217;s grace (&#8220;graciously given&#8221; is the verb hanan, grace). The children as gift of divine grace &#8212; not achievement but grace &#8212; is the pattern of the new covenant: &#8220;children born not of natural descent&#8230; but born of God&#8221; (John 1:13). The church as the children God has graciously given to Christ is explicit in John 17:6: &#8220;I have revealed you to those whom you gave me out of the world. They were yours; you gave them to me.&#8221; Christ can say to the Father about the church what Jacob says to Esau about his children: these are those you graciously gave me.</p>",
"6": "<p>The female servants and their children approached and bowed down &#8212; the covenant family&#8217;s approach to the one they feared as a threat, now received in peace. The approach of those who were vulnerable &#8212; the servants, the children, then the wives &#8212; to the one who could have been a destroyer corresponds to the access that Christ&#8217;s reconciliation opens: &#8220;in him and through faith in him we may approach God with freedom and confidence&#8221; (Eph 3:12). The fearful approach becomes bold access through the prior reconciliation. Esau&#8217;s embrace of Jacob makes the approach of the household possible; Christ&#8217;s reconciliation with the Father makes the church&#8217;s approach to God possible.</p>",
"7": "<p>Next, Leah and her children came and bowed down. Last of all came Joseph and Rachel, and they too bowed down &#8212; all of Jacob&#8217;s household bows before Esau in an act of covenant submission. The bowing of Joseph and Rachel before Esau foreshadows Joseph&#8217;s later experience: the dreams of ch37 show sheaves and stars bowing to Joseph &#8212; and this scene of Joseph himself bowing (with his household) before Esau prefigures the great reversal. The humility that precedes exaltation is the pattern of Christ: &#8220;he humbled himself&#8230; therefore God exalted him&#8221; (Phil 2:8&#8211;9). Joseph and Rachel bowing now; Joseph exalted later &#8212; the Christ-pattern of descent and ascent.</p>",
"8": "<p>Esau asked, &#8220;What&#8217;s the meaning of all these flocks and herds I met?&#8221; &#8212; Esau encounters the gift-procession Jacob had sent ahead (ch32:13&#8211;21). Jacob&#8217;s gifts sent ahead to &#8220;appease&#8221; Esau are the OT gift of reconciliation: the offender sending gifts to the offended before the encounter. The NT equivalent is Christ&#8217;s atonement as the prior reconciliation that enables the meeting: &#8220;we were reconciled to him through the death of his Son&#8221; (Rom 5:10) &#8212; the reconciliation was achieved before we sought it. God&#8217;s gift of Christ (the prior gift) precedes our encounter with him, just as Jacob&#8217;s gifts preceded his encounter with Esau.</p>",
"9": "<p>Esau said, &#8220;I already have plenty, my brother. Keep what you have for yourself&#8221; &#8212; Esau&#8217;s gracious refusal of the gift he did not need. The one who has been wronged who says &#8220;I have enough&#8221; is the picture of grace rather than transactional justice: Esau could demand restitution for the stolen blessing but instead declares sufficiency. The God who does not need anything from us but receives us anyway is the NT posture: &#8220;The God who made the world and everything in it&#8230; is not served by human hands, as if he needed anything&#8221; (Acts 17:24&#8211;25). Grace does not need to be appeased by our gifts; grace already has plenty and meets us out of abundance, not need.</p>",
"10": "<p>&#8220;No, please!&#8221; said Jacob. &#8220;If I have found favor in your eyes, accept this gift from me. For to see your face is like seeing the face of God, now that you have received me favorably&#8221; &#8212; &#8220;to see your face is like seeing the face of God&#8221; &#8212; one of the most theologically loaded statements in Genesis. After his experience of wrestling God at Peniel (&#8220;I saw God face to face,&#8221; 32:30), Jacob now sees God&#8217;s face in the face of his reconciled brother. The face of God is revealed in the act of unexpected forgiveness and acceptance. John 1:18: &#8220;No one has ever seen God, but the one and only Son, who is himself God and is in closest relationship with the Father, has made him known.&#8221; 2 Cor 4:6: &#8220;the light of the knowledge of God&#8217;s glory displayed in the face of Christ.&#8221; The face of God Jacob sees in Esau&#8217;s reconciling reception is fully revealed in Christ&#8217;s face &#8212; the face of God&#8217;s grace toward the sinner.</p>",
"11": "<p>&#8220;Please accept the blessing I have brought you, for God has been gracious to me and I have all I need.&#8221; And because Jacob insisted, Esau accepted it &#8212; Jacob returns a blessing to Esau &#8212; the reversal of ch27 where he stole the blessing. The restoration of the blessing to the one from whom it was taken is the type of Christ&#8217;s restorative work: &#8220;I restore what I did not steal&#8221; (Ps 69:4, applied typologically to Christ). Jacob restores what he did steal; Christ restores the blessing to humanity &#8212; the blessing forfeited in the fall &#8212; though Christ himself stole nothing. The gracious giving of blessing to the one who was wronged is the shape of the gospel: God does not merely forgive the debt but gives the inheritance of blessing to those who forfeited it.</p>",
"12": "<p>Then Esau said, &#8220;Let us be on our way; I&#8217;ll accompany you&#8221; &#8212; Esau&#8217;s offer of escort: the reconciled enemy who becomes companion for the journey. The protection of the covenant-bearer by the very one who had threatened him is the type of God turning enemies into instruments of protection: &#8220;When a man&#8217;s ways please the LORD, he makes even his enemies to be at peace with him&#8221; (Prov 16:7). Christ prayed for his enemies and from the cross said, &#8220;Father, forgive them&#8221; (Luke 23:34) &#8212; the ultimate act of turning enemies into companions. The eschatological vision includes former enemies walking together in peace: &#8220;They will beat their swords into plowshares&#8221; (Isa 2:4).</p>",
"13": "<p>Jacob said to him, &#8220;My lord knows that the children are tender and that I must care for the ewes and cows that are nursing their young&#8221; &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s pastoral concern for the tender and the nursing: he cannot move at Esau&#8217;s military pace. The shepherd who adjusts the pace of travel to the weakest members of the flock is the type of Christ&#8217;s pastoral patience. Isaiah 40:11: &#8220;He tends his flock like a shepherd: He gathers the lambs in his arms and carries them close to his heart; he gently leads those that have young.&#8221; The same verse pattern is reflected here: Jacob leads gently because of the nursing ewes; the Good Shepherd leads gently because of those who are weak and cannot travel at the pace of the strong.</p>",
"14": "<p>&#8220;So let my lord go on ahead of his servant, while I move along slowly at the pace of the flocks and herds before me and the pace of the children&#8221; &#8212; Jacob moves at the pace of the slowest &#8212; the children and the nursing animals. The leader who sets the pace not by his own capability but by the neediest in his care is the type of Christ&#8217;s ministry: &#8220;A bruised reed he will not break, and a smoldering wick he will not snuff out&#8221; (Matt 12:20, citing Isa 42:3). Christ does not demand that the weak move at the pace of the strong; he stoops to the pace of the broken and fragile. The entire incarnation is God moving at the pace of his creature: &#8220;the Word became flesh&#8221; (John 1:14) &#8212; the infinite accommodating itself to the finite&#8217;s pace.</p>",
"15": "<p>Esau offered to leave some men with Jacob; Jacob graciously declined &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s confident refusal of Esau&#8217;s armed escort shows that his protection comes from God, not from Esau&#8217;s men. The covenant-bearer who trusts divine protection over human protection is the type of the Christian&#8217;s confidence: &#8220;The LORD is my shepherd, I lack nothing&#8221; (Ps 23:1); &#8220;The LORD is my light and my salvation &#8212; whom shall I fear?&#8221; (Ps 27:1). Christ taught the same trust: &#8220;do not worry about your life&#8230; your heavenly Father feeds them&#8221; (Matt 6:25&#8211;26). The covenant-bearer&#8217;s gracious declining of human security in favor of divine protection is the posture of faith that Christ embodies and commends.</p>",
"16": "<p>So that day Esau started on his way back to Seir &#8212; the separation of Esau and Jacob after the reconciliation. The two brothers part ways after the emotional reunion; Esau returns to Seir (Edom, outside the covenant land) and Jacob continues toward Succoth and then Canaan. The permanent separation of the two lines &#8212; Esau to Edom, Jacob to Israel &#8212; is the covenant distinction. Paul in Rom 9:13 (citing Mal 1:2&#8211;3: &#8220;Jacob I loved, but Esau I hated&#8221;) develops this separation as the type of divine election: the covenant community is separated from the non-covenant by divine choice, not human achievement &#8212; though both are fully human, fully real brothers.</p>",
"17": "<p>Jacob went to Succoth, where he built a place for himself and made shelters for his livestock &#8212; Succoth (&#8220;shelters/booths&#8221;) gives the town its name. The building of shelters (sukkot) connects to the Feast of Tabernacles (Sukkoth), which the Torah instituted as a memorial of Israel&#8217;s wilderness sheltering (Lev 23:42&#8211;43). The Feast of Tabernacles in turn becomes the type of the eschatological &#8220;tenting&#8221; of God with his people: John 1:14 (&#8220;the Word became flesh and made his dwelling among us&#8221; &#8212; eskēnōsen, lit. &#8220;tabernacled&#8221;) and Rev 21:3 (&#8220;God&#8217;s dwelling place is now among the people&#8221;). Jacob&#8217;s shelter at Succoth is a faint type of the divine sheltering that Christ&#8217;s incarnation and the eschatological state fully express.</p>",
"18": "<p>Jacob came from Paddan Aram and arrived safely at the city of Shechem in Canaan &#8212; the safe return to Canaan after 20 years in Paddan Aram. &#8220;Arrived safely&#8221; (shālem &#8212; whole/complete/at peace) is the arrival of the covenant-bearer back in the covenant land in a state of shalom. The peace-arrival back in the promised land is the type of the ultimate arrival in the promised rest: &#8220;There remains, then, a Sabbath-rest for the people of God&#8221; (Heb 4:9); the journey through exile is finally complete. Christ is the one who arrives in peace &#8212; &#8220;Peace I leave with you; my peace I give you&#8221; (John 14:27) &#8212; and who opens the way back to the Father&#8217;s presence, the ultimate &#8220;Canaan.&#8221;</p>",
"19": "<p>He bought from the sons of Hamor the plot of ground where he pitched his tent &#8212; Jacob purchases land at Shechem. Stephen mentions this land in his speech: &#8220;Jacob went down to Egypt, where he and our ancestors died. Their bodies were brought back to Shechem and placed in the tomb that Abraham had bought&#8221; (Acts 7:15&#8211;16). The purchased land at Shechem becomes a burial ground &#8212; a death-land &#8212; before it becomes a resurrection-land (for the people of God who inherit the earth, Matt 5:5). The covenant-bearer&#8217;s purchase of a small plot in the promised land is the down payment of the full inheritance: &#8220;he gave him no inheritance here, not even enough ground to set his foot on. But God promised him that he and his descendants after him would possess the land&#8221; (Acts 7:5).</p>",
"20": "<p>There he set up an altar and called it El Elohe Israel &#8212; &#8220;God, the God of Israel&#8221;. The first altar Jacob builds after his return to Canaan is named with the covenant formula: the personal relationship between God and the man whose name is now Israel. The covenant name &#8220;God of Israel&#8221; runs through the entire OT (&#8220;the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob&#8221; &#8212; Matt 22:32; Exod 3:6; Acts 7:32) and reaches its fullest expression in Christ: &#8220;I am the God of your fathers&#8230; I have indeed seen the misery of my people&#8230; I am sending you&#8221; (Acts 7:33&#8211;34). The God who names himself by covenant relationship &#8212; God-of-Israel &#8212; is the same God who says &#8220;I am the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ&#8221; (Eph 1:3; 2 Cor 1:3). The altar built with the covenant name is the worship posture of those who know God by his relationship to his people.</p>",
},
"34": {
"1": "<p>Dinah, the daughter Leah had borne to Jacob, went out to visit the women of the land &#8212; Dinah&#8217;s going out to the women of Canaan is presented without moral comment; visiting neighboring women was ordinary life. The vulnerability of the covenant community&#8217;s members when they &#8220;go out&#8221; into the surrounding world is a recurring concern. The church lives &#8220;in the world but not of the world&#8221; (John 17:11&#8211;16) &#8212; present in the surrounding culture, not cloistered, but exposed to its dangers. Christ prays not that the Father would &#8220;take them out of the world but that you protect them from the evil one&#8221; (John 17:15). The covenant community&#8217;s exposure to the world is not the problem; the world&#8217;s violation of the covenant community is the sin.</p>",
"2": "<p>Shechem son of Hamor&#8230; saw her, he took her and raped her &#8212; the assault on Dinah is blunt in the Hebrew: he took, he lay with, he violated her. The violation of the innocent by power is the fundamental form of sin &#8212; the strong taking from the weak what they have no right to take. The entire passion narrative shows Christ &#8220;taken&#8221; by those in power (Matt 26:50: &#8220;they came forward, seized Jesus&#8221;), unjustly treated. But Christ takes on himself not only the suffering of the violated but also the guilt of the violators: &#8220;he was pierced for our transgressions&#8221; (Isa 53:5). Shechem&#8217;s sin and its consequences become the type of sin&#8217;s injury &#8212; both to the victim and through the cycle of revenge it generates &#8212; that Christ bears to break.</p>",
"3": "<p>His heart was drawn to Dinah; he loved the young woman and spoke tenderly to her &#8212; Shechem&#8217;s tender words after the assault. The violence followed by soft words is the pattern of exploitation that uses emotional language to reframe wrongdoing. The prophets name this precisely: false prophets who &#8220;heal the wound of my people lightly, saying &#8216;Peace, peace&#8217; when there is no peace&#8221; (Jer 6:14). The tender speech that does not undo the harm it attempts to cover is the religious and moral danger that Christ names: &#8220;Watch out for false prophets. They come to you in sheep&#8217;s clothing&#8221; (Matt 7:15). The violence of sin cannot be made right by tender words; only the blood of the covenant achieves genuine reconciliation (Heb 9:22).</p>",
"4": "<p>Shechem said to his father Hamor, &#8220;Get me this girl as my wife&#8221; &#8212; the demand for marriage after the assault. Shechem wants covenant relationship (marriage) after covenant violation (rape). The desire to regularize sin through formal relationship &#8212; to make right through structure what was wrong in act &#8212; is the human attempt to substitute form for genuine repentance. Christ refuses the form without the substance: &#8220;Not everyone who says to me, &#8216;Lord, Lord,&#8217; will enter the kingdom of heaven, but only the one who does the will of my Father who is in heaven&#8221; (Matt 7:21). The confession of &#8220;Lord&#8221; without the transformation of life is the Shechem-pattern: claiming covenant relationship without covenant transformation.</p>",
"5": "<p>When Jacob heard that his daughter Dinah had been defiled, his sons were in the fields; so he said nothing about it until they came home &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s silence. The father who knows of his daughter&#8217;s assault and says nothing &#8212; waiting for the sons &#8212; is a disturbing image of covenant leadership that defers action. The contrast with the divine Father: God does not wait and defer when his people are violated; &#8220;he has not despised or scorned the suffering of the afflicted one; he has not hidden his face from him but has listened to his cry for help&#8221; (Ps 22:24). Christ acts immediately when the suffering cry reaches him: &#8220;he was moved with compassion&#8221; (Matt 9:36; 14:14; 15:32) &#8212; the opposite of the silence that defers action.</p>",
"6": "<p>Shechem&#8217;s father Hamor went out to talk with Jacob &#8212; Hamor&#8217;s diplomatic approach. The attempt to negotiate a settlement for an act that requires justice rather than negotiation is the misapplication of diplomacy to moral wrong. The NT is clear that justice cannot be bartered away: &#8220;Do not take revenge, my dear friends, but leave room for God&#8217;s wrath, for it is written: &#8216;It is mine to avenge; I will repay,&#8217; says the Lord&#8221; (Rom 12:19). Christ does not negotiate sin away; he pays sin&#8217;s penalty in full. The cross is not a settlement but a satisfaction: &#8220;he is the propitiation for our sins&#8221; (1 John 2:2 ESV) &#8212; the sin is not managed but absorbed and paid.</p>",
"7": "<p>Jacob&#8217;s sons had come in from the fields; they were shocked and furious, because Shechem had done a disgraceful thing in Israel &#8212; the brothers&#8217; righteous outrage at the violation of their sister. The anger is called righteous by the narrative&#8217;s framing: the act was genuinely &#8220;a disgraceful thing in Israel&#8221; (nebalah be-yisra&#8217;el), a phrase the OT uses for acts that violate the covenant community&#8217;s order (Deut 22:21; 2 Sam 13:12). Christ is the one who takes righteous anger seriously: &#8220;he made a whip out of cords, and drove all from the temple courts&#8221; (John 2:15). The indignation at genuine injustice is not sin but the proper moral response. The brothers&#8217; anger is not wrong; their response (vv25&#8211;29) exceeds justice into vengeance.</p>",
"8": "<p>Hamor said to them, &#8220;My son Shechem has his heart set on your daughter. Please give her to him as his wife&#8221; &#8212; Hamor&#8217;s request reframes the assault as romance: Shechem&#8217;s &#8220;heart is set on&#8221; Dinah, as if the violence were simply ardent love. The narrative&#8217;s earlier precision (&#8220;took her and raped her,&#8221; v2) is the counterweight to Hamor&#8217;s romantic framing. The reframing of sin as something other than what it is &#8212; the softening language that makes wrongdoing palatable &#8212; is what Paul calls &#8220;exchanging the truth about God for a lie&#8221; (Rom 1:25). Christ insists on naming sin as sin: &#8220;For out of the heart come evil thoughts &#8212; murder, adultery, sexual immorality&#8221; (Matt 15:19). The naming of sin truthfully is the first step of the gospel.</p>",
"9": "<p>&#8220;Intermarry with us; give us your daughters and take our daughters for yourselves&#8221; &#8212; Hamor&#8217;s proposal of intermarriage. The absorption of the covenant community into the surrounding culture through intermarriage was consistently the path that diluted the covenant (as later in Israel&#8217;s history &#8212; Deut 7:3&#8211;4; Ezra 9&#8211;10). The covenant community&#8217;s distinctiveness is essential to its witness. Paul in 2 Cor 6:14&#8211;18: &#8220;Do not be yoked together with unbelievers&#8230; What does a believer have in common with an unbeliever?&#8221; The distinctiveness that Hamor&#8217;s proposal would dissolve is preserved in the church by the covenant identity that Christ gives: &#8220;a chosen people, a royal priesthood, a holy nation&#8221; (1 Pet 2:9).</p>",
"10": "<p>&#8220;You can settle among us; the land is open to you. Live in it, trade in it, and acquire property in it&#8221; &#8212; the generous-sounding offer: the covenant community is invited to assimilate. The world&#8217;s consistent offer to the covenant community is assimilation in exchange for comfort and security: &#8220;live among us, trade, acquire&#8221; &#8212; the material benefits of belonging. Christ describes the alternative: &#8220;Do not store up for yourselves treasures on earth&#8230; But store up for yourselves treasures in heaven&#8221; (Matt 6:19&#8211;20). The offer of land, trade, and property is not inherently wrong, but when it comes at the cost of covenant identity, the covenant community must say no. The covenant-bearer&#8217;s relationship with surrounding culture requires wisdom, not assimilation.</p>",
"11": "<p>Shechem said, &#8220;Let me find favor in your eyes, and I will give you whatever you ask&#8221; &#8212; Shechem&#8217;s personal appeal alongside his father&#8217;s diplomatic proposal. &#8220;Let me find favor in your eyes&#8221; is the grace-language of the covenant applied by an outsider seeking covenant inclusion. The genuine desire for covenant belonging that Shechem expresses &#8212; however compromised by the context &#8212; is the type of the Gentile longing to be included in God&#8217;s covenant. Paul&#8217;s gospel is the legitimate fulfillment of this longing: &#8220;you who once were far away have been brought near by the blood of Christ&#8221; (Eph 2:13). Christ is the one who genuinely opens covenant inclusion to all who seek it &#8212; without the violence and deception that mark this episode.</p>",
"12": "<p>&#8220;Make the price for the bride and the gift as great as you like, and I&#8217;ll pay whatever you ask&#8221; &#8212; Shechem offers unlimited bride-price. The willingness to pay any price for the beloved is a genuine virtue that the covenant context has corrupted: the wrongdoing preceded the negotiation. But the pattern of paying any price for the bride is the type of Christ&#8217;s atoning purchase: &#8220;you were bought at a price&#8221; (1 Cor 6:20; 7:23); &#8220;the church of God, which he bought with his own blood&#8221; (Acts 20:28). The difference: Christ&#8217;s payment purchases what he has rightful claim to; Shechem&#8217;s payment attempts to purchase what his violence forfeited. The bride-price of the gospel is the blood of Christ, not silver or gold (1 Pet 1:18&#8211;19).</p>",
"13": "<p>Jacob&#8217;s sons replied deceitfully as they spoke to Shechem and his father Hamor &#8212; the deception-pattern continues into the next generation. The sons of Jacob, like their father (who deceived Laban and Isaac), respond to Shechem with deceit. The moral inheritance of deception &#8212; the sin of the father visited on the children (Exod 20:5) &#8212; is the OT&#8217;s realistic account of how sin propagates through families. Christ comes to break this generational pattern: &#8220;everyone who sins is a slave to sin&#8221; (John 8:34) &#8212; but &#8220;if the Son sets you free, you will be free indeed&#8221; (John 8:36). The liberation from the inherited patterns of deception and violence is the gospel&#8217;s specific promise to those entangled in generational sin.</p>",
"14": "<p>&#8220;We can&#8217;t give our sister to a man who is not circumcised. That would be a disgrace to us&#8221; &#8212; the brothers use circumcision as the pretext for their plan. Circumcision as the covenant sign being weaponized as a tool of deception is a profound corruption of the covenant. Paul in Gal 5:6 strips circumcision of its power as a legal requirement: &#8220;neither circumcision nor uncircumcision has any value&#8221; &#8212; what matters is &#8220;faith expressing itself through love.&#8221; The brothers use circumcision as a tool of violence; Paul says circumcision used as a tool of coercion is no better (Gal 5:2&#8211;3). The covenant sign is meant to mark covenant belonging, not to serve as a weapon in human schemes.</p>",
"15": "<p>&#8220;We will enter into an agreement with you on one condition only: that you become like us by circumcising all your males&#8221; &#8212; the demand for circumcision as the price of covenant inclusion. Simeon and Levi use the covenant requirement as a pretext &#8212; not as a genuine invitation to covenant membership but as a means of incapacitation. The use of religious requirements as instruments of power and manipulation is what the NT calls &#8220;burdening with a yoke that neither we nor our ancestors have been able to bear&#8221; (Acts 15:10). Christ does not use covenant requirements as instruments of manipulation: &#8220;Come to me&#8230; my yoke is easy and my burden is light&#8221; (Matt 11:28&#8211;30). The covenant entrance that Christ offers is genuine, not a trap.</p>",
"16": "<p>&#8220;Then we will give you our daughters and take your daughters for ourselves. We&#8217;ll settle among you and become one people with you&#8221; &#8212; the brothers&#8217; false promise of unity. The promise of becoming &#8220;one people&#8221; that will not be kept is a counterfeit of the genuine unity that Christ brings. John 17:21: &#8220;that all of them may be one, Father, just as you are in me and I am in you &#8212; so that the world may believe that you have sent me.&#8221; The genuine oneness of the covenant community in Christ is the fulfillment of the hope for unity that these negotiations corrupt. The brothers&#8217; false &#8220;one people&#8221; is overtaken by Christ&#8217;s genuine &#8220;one flock, one shepherd&#8221; (John 10:16).</p>",
"17": "<p>&#8220;But if you will not agree to be circumcised, we&#8217;ll take our sister and go&#8221; &#8212; the ultimatum. The covenant community&#8217;s ultimatum to the surrounding world &#8212; accept our terms or we depart &#8212; is a legitimate posture when the terms are genuine covenant rather than a trap. Paul&#8217;s principle: &#8220;What do I have to do with judging those outside? Are you not to judge those inside? God will judge those outside&#8221; (1 Cor 5:12&#8211;13). The covenant community does not force its terms on the surrounding world; it maintains its distinctiveness and departs when its integrity is threatened. Here the ultimatum is a deception; but the underlying principle of covenant distinctiveness is genuine.</p>",
"18": "<p>Their proposal seemed good to Hamor and his son Shechem &#8212; the Shechemites accept the terms. The acceptance of the covenant requirement (circumcision) without genuine covenant commitment &#8212; for strategic rather than faith reasons (v23: &#8220;won&#8217;t their livestock become ours?&#8221;) &#8212; is the type of the false conversion that takes the form of covenant without the substance. James 2:19: &#8220;even the demons believe &#8212; and shudder.&#8221; The mere acceptance of external religious requirements without the transformation of the heart is what Paul calls &#8220;a form of godliness but denying its power&#8221; (2 Tim 3:5). True covenant membership is circumcision of the heart (Rom 2:29; Deut 10:16), not merely the flesh.</p>",
"19": "<p>The young man lost no time in doing what they said, because he was delighted with Jacob&#8217;s daughter &#8212; Shechem&#8217;s eager compliance, motivated by desire for Dinah rather than covenant faith. The action without the right motivation is the type of religious observance without genuine faith: &#8220;These people honor me with their lips, but their hearts are far from me&#8221; (Matt 15:8, citing Isa 29:13). The speed of Shechem&#8217;s compliance &#8212; &#8220;lost no time&#8221; &#8212; is motivated by self-interest (wanting Dinah) not by covenant belonging. Christ sees through external compliance to the motive: &#8220;Man looks at the outward appearance, but the LORD looks at the heart&#8221; (1 Sam 16:7, cited in context of Christ&#8217;s insight: John 2:25: &#8220;he knew what was in each person&#8221;).</p>",
"20": "<p>Hamor and his son Shechem went to the gate of their city to speak to the men of their city &#8212; the city gate as the place of public deliberation and covenant-making. The gate is the place of law and community decision (Ruth 4:1&#8211;11; Deut 21:19). The covenant negotiation being conducted publicly at the gate &#8212; the legitimate procedure &#8212; is being used here for a scheme that is not legitimate. The formal structures of justice and community deliberation &#8212; good in themselves &#8212; can be corrupted by those who use them for unjust ends. Christ&#8217;s trial before Pilate is the supreme example: legitimate judicial procedure (the governor, the legal accusation, the public hearing) used to execute an unjust verdict on the one who had done nothing wrong (Luke 23:4: &#8220;I find no basis for a charge against this man&#8221;).</p>",
"21": "<p>&#8220;These men are friendly toward us. Let them live in our land&#8221; &#8212; Hamor&#8217;s community speech reframes the covenant negotiation as straightforward friendship and mutual benefit. The language of friendliness and mutual gain that conceals the full picture &#8212; Shechem&#8217;s assault, the brothers&#8217; deception &#8212; is the selective truth-telling that the NT consistently condemns: &#8220;speaking the truth in love&#8221; (Eph 4:15) requires the whole truth, not the convenient portion. Christ promises the Spirit of Truth who will &#8220;guide you into all the truth&#8221; (John 16:13) &#8212; the complete, not selective, disclosure that covenant relationship requires.</p>",
"22": "<p>&#8220;The men will agree to live with us as one people only on the condition that our males be circumcised, as they themselves are&#8221; &#8212; Hamor reports the condition honestly to his city. At least at this level &#8212; in reporting the terms to his own people &#8212; Hamor is straightforward. The partial honesty that operates within one&#8217;s own community while being deceptive toward the covenant community is the normal operating mode of the world&#8217;s engagement with the church. Christ calls his disciples to a higher standard: &#8220;Let your &#8216;Yes&#8217; be &#8216;Yes,&#8217; and your &#8216;No,&#8217; &#8216;No&#8217;&#8221; (Matt 5:37) &#8212; consistency in truth-telling across all relationships, not merely within the in-group.</p>",
"23": "<p>&#8220;Won&#8217;t their livestock, their property and all their other animals become ours?&#8221; &#8212; the economic motivation for the Shechemites&#8217; agreement: they calculate that accepting circumcision will eventually transfer the covenant family&#8217;s wealth to them. The acceptance of covenant forms for economic benefit &#8212; the prosperity gospel inverted &#8212; is the constant temptation to use religious allegiance for material gain. Paul warns Timothy: &#8220;godliness with contentment is great gain&#8221; (1 Tim 6:6) but those who think &#8220;godliness is a means to financial gain&#8221; (v5) are corrupted. Christ explicitly refused material benefit as a motivation for following him: &#8220;Do not work for food that spoils, but for food that endures to eternal life&#8221; (John 6:27).</p>",
"24": "<p>All the men who went out of the city gate agreed&#8230; and every male in the city was circumcised &#8212; the mass circumcision of the Shechemites. The entire male population submitting to the covenant sign without covenant faith is the type of the mass religious conformity that the prophets consistently condemned: &#8220;This people draws near to me with their mouth and honors me with their lips, while their hearts are far from me&#8221; (Isa 29:13; Matt 15:8). The circumcision of the flesh without the circumcision of the heart (Jer 4:4; Rom 2:29) is the perpetual religious failure. Christ comes to accomplish what mass circumcision cannot: &#8220;In him you were also circumcised with a circumcision not performed by human hands&#8230; the circumcision of Christ&#8221; (Col 2:11).</p>",
"25": "<p>Three days later, while all of them were still in pain, two of Jacob&#8217;s sons, Simeon and Levi, took their swords and attacked the unsuspecting city, killing every male &#8212; the massacre on the third day. Simeon and Levi exploit the incapacitation that the covenant sign has caused to carry out their revenge. The perversion of the covenant sign &#8212; used to make victims of those who accepted it &#8212; is one of the darkest actions in Genesis. The righteous anger (v7) becomes righteous murder by the logic of revenge. Paul&#8217;s warning: &#8220;Do not be overcome by evil, but overcome evil with good&#8221; (Rom 12:21). Christ overcomes the evil of the cross not by returning violence but by absorbing it and transforming it through the resurrection. The Simeon-and-Levi response is the way of the world; the cross is the way of God.</p>",
"26": "<p>They put Hamor and his son Shechem to the sword and took Dinah from Shechem&#8217;s house and left &#8212; Dinah is retrieved from Shechem&#8217;s house &#8212; she had apparently been kept there. The liberation of Dinah is the only righteous element of the brothers&#8217; action; the slaughter of the entire city goes far beyond what justice required. Christ&#8217;s liberation is precise and proportionate: he bears exactly the penalty that sin requires (no more, no less) and liberates exactly those for whom he died. The liberation of Dinah at the cost of disproportionate violence is the contrast with the liberation of sinners at the precisely proportionate cost of Christ&#8217;s atoning death: &#8220;the righteous for the unrighteous, to bring you to God&#8221; (1 Pet 3:18).</p>",
"27": "<p>The sons of Jacob came upon the dead and looted the city &#8212; the wider looting carried out by the other brothers after Simeon and Levi&#8217;s attack. The violence expands beyond the two initiators: the other sons join in the looting. Sin consistently spreads: the initial violence creates an environment in which further sin becomes acceptable. &#8220;A little yeast leavens the whole batch of dough&#8221; (Gal 5:9; 1 Cor 5:6). The same principle that Paul applies to the corrupting influence of false teaching applies to the corrupting influence of violence: once begun, it spreads through the whole. Christ alone can stop the spread: &#8220;The blood of Jesus, his Son, purifies us from all sin&#8221; (1 John 1:7).</p>",
"28": "<p>They seized their flocks and herds and donkeys and everything else in the city and out in the fields &#8212; the systematic plundering of the Shechemites&#8217; property. The taking of property from those who were killed follows the logic of warfare-as-plunder that runs through the ancient world. The contrast with Christ: at the cross, the soldiers divided his garments (Matt 27:35, fulfilling Ps 22:18) &#8212; the covenant-bearer&#8217;s property distributed among his enemies. Where Jacob&#8217;s sons took the property of those they killed, the soldiers took Christ&#8217;s property while killing him. The reversal is the shape of the cross: not the victorious one who plunders, but the innocent one who is plundered for the sins of others.</p>",
"29": "<p>They carried off all their wealth and all their women and children, taking as plunder everything in the houses &#8212; the enslavement of the Shechemite women and children. The victors who enslave the defeated is the ancient world&#8217;s normal outcome of warfare; the moral catastrophe is presented without whitewash. Jacob&#8217;s rebuke (v30) and his deathbed curse of Simeon and Levi (49:5&#8211;7) show the narrative&#8217;s moral judgment on the action. Christ comes to reverse the victor-enslaves-the-defeated logic: &#8220;For the Son of Man came not to be served but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many&#8221; (Mark 10:45). The ransom liberates the enslaved; the covenant-bearer&#8217;s death sets free those whom violence had captivated.</p>",
"30": "<p>Then Jacob said to Simeon and Levi, &#8220;You have brought trouble on me by making me obnoxious to the Canaanites and Perizzites&#8221; &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s rebuke focuses on the practical danger to the covenant family (the surrounding nations may retaliate) rather than the moral wrong done to the Shechemites. Jacob&#8217;s self-centered rebuke contrasts with God&#8217;s comprehensive moral vision. The prophets will later indict Israel&#8217;s leaders for the same failure: rebuking wrongdoing not because it was wrong but because it was inconvenient: &#8220;Woe to those who call evil good and good evil&#8221; (Isa 5:20). Christ&#8217;s moral vision is comprehensive: he weeps over Jerusalem not because it is dangerous for him but because of what Jerusalem is doing to itself (Luke 19:41&#8211;44). The covenant-bearer who sees the full moral picture rather than the convenient one.</p>",
"31": "<p>But they replied, &#8220;Should he have treated our sister like a prostitute?&#8221; &#8212; Simeon and Levi&#8217;s final word, which the narrative gives them without refutation. Their defense is morally coherent &#8212; Shechem&#8217;s treatment of Dinah was genuinely wrong &#8212; even if their response was disproportionate. The unanswered question that closes ch34 is the OT&#8217;s honest reckoning with the gap between moral outrage and moral response: righteous anger does not automatically produce righteous action. Christ addresses this gap: &#8220;In your anger do not sin&#8221; (Eph 4:26, citing Ps 4:4). The anger at genuine injustice is legitimate; the channeling of that anger into violence that exceeds justice is the failure. The brothers&#8217; unanswered question awaits the answer that the cross provides: injustice is answered not by counter-violence but by the bearing of its full weight.</p>",
},
"35": {
"1": "<p>God said to Jacob, &#8220;Go up to Bethel and settle there, and build an altar there to God, who appeared to you when you were fleeing from your brother Esau&#8221; &#8212; after the violence of ch34, God calls Jacob back to Bethel &#8212; the place of the first covenant encounter (ch28). The divine call to return to the place of first encounter after moral failure is the pattern of renewal through return to the covenant. The prophets consistently call Israel back: &#8220;Return to me, and I will return to you&#8221; (Mal 3:7). Christ is the fulfillment: &#8220;I will come back and take you to be with me&#8221; (John 14:3). The command to go up to Bethel (&#8220;house of God&#8221;) is the type of Christ&#8217;s invitation: &#8220;Come to me, all you who are weary&#8221; (Matt 11:28). The place of God&#8217;s presence is always the place to return to after moral failure.</p>",
"2": "<p>Jacob said to his household, &#8220;Get rid of the foreign gods you have with you, and purify yourselves and change your clothes&#8221; &#8212; the call to put away idols, purify, and change garments before ascending to Bethel. The threefold preparation (put away idols, purify, change clothes) is the OT&#8217;s type of baptism and repentance: &#8220;Do not conform to the pattern of this world, but be transformed by the renewing of your mind&#8221; (Rom 12:2). The changing of garments is the type of putting on Christ: &#8220;clothe yourselves with the Lord Jesus Christ&#8221; (Rom 13:14); &#8220;put on the new self&#8221; (Eph 4:24). Before ascending to the house of God, the covenant community must shed what belongs to the old life. The preparation for worship is moral and spiritual transformation.</p>",
"3": "<p>&#8220;Then come, let us go up to Bethel, where I will build an altar to God, who answered me in the day of my distress and who has been with me wherever I have gone&#8221; &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s testimony: &#8220;God&#8230; who answered me in the day of my distress and who has been with me wherever I have gone.&#8221; The God who answers in distress and accompanies through all journeys is the covenant God who becomes fully present in Christ: &#8220;God with us&#8221; (Matt 1:23, Emmanuel); &#8220;I am with you always, to the very end of the age&#8221; (Matt 28:20). The pattern of God&#8217;s answering and accompanying &#8212; which Jacob testifies to from his 20 years of exile and return &#8212; is the pattern that Christ embodies in its fullness: always present, always answering, accompanying through all distress.</p>",
"4": "<p>They gave Jacob all the foreign gods they had and the rings in their ears, and Jacob buried them under the oak at Shechem &#8212; the household gives up their idols and earrings (perhaps connected to idolatrous use). The burial of idols before ascending to Bethel is the type of putting off the old self: &#8220;You were taught&#8230; to put off your old self, which is being corrupted by its deceitful desires&#8221; (Eph 4:22). The burying of the foreign gods under an oak at Shechem is the type of the definitive end of the old religious identity before the new covenant worship. Baptism in the NT is this burial: &#8220;We were therefore buried with him through baptism into death in order that, just as Christ was raised from the dead&#8230; we too may live a new life&#8221; (Rom 6:4). The buried idols are the type of the buried old self.</p>",
"5": "<p>The terror of God fell on the towns all around them so that no one pursued them &#8212; divine protection through the &#8220;terror of God&#8221; (hitat Elohim) that falls on the surrounding towns. The covenant community returning to the place of worship is supernaturally protected. This is the pattern of Exod 23:27 (&#8220;I will send my terror ahead of you&#8221;) and Josh 2:9 (Rahab: &#8220;a great fear of you has fallen on us&#8221;). The divine protection of the covenant community on its journey to worship is the type of Christ&#8217;s promise: &#8220;I will build my church, and the gates of Hades will not overcome it&#8221; (Matt 16:18). The church on its pilgrimage to the heavenly Bethel is protected by the same divine terror that cleared the way for Jacob&#8217;s household.</p>",
"6": "<p>Jacob and all the people with him came to Luz (that is, Bethel) in the land of Canaan &#8212; the arrival at Bethel after the purification journey from Shechem. Luz is the ancient name; Bethel (&#8220;house of God&#8221;) is the covenant name Jacob gave it after his dream in ch28. The place renamed by covenant encounter: the ordinary Canaanite town (Luz) becomes &#8220;house of God&#8221; by the divine visitation. Christ transforms places by his presence: Galilee of the Gentiles becomes the place of great light (Matt 4:15&#8211;16; Isa 9:1&#8211;2). The ordinary &#8212; Luz, Galilee, the upper room &#8212; becomes the &#8220;house of God&#8221; by the divine encounter. Every place where Christ is present is Bethel.</p>",
"7": "<p>There he built an altar, and he called the place El Bethel &#8212; &#8220;God of Bethel&#8221; &#8212; because it was there that God had revealed himself to him when he was fleeing from his brother &#8212; the altar&#8217;s name commemorates the specific act of divine revelation: &#8220;God revealed himself&#8230; when he was fleeing.&#8221; God reveals himself most profoundly at moments of flight, desperation, and vulnerability &#8212; not in triumph. Christ&#8217;s revelation of God comes not in triumph but in the incarnation&#8217;s vulnerability: &#8220;God, who is rich in mercy, made us alive with Christ even when we were dead in transgressions&#8221; (Eph 2:4&#8211;5). The altar&#8217;s name &#8220;El Bethel&#8221; is the covenant testimony that God&#8217;s self-revelation comes to those who are fleeing and vulnerable, not to those who are secure and strong.</p>",
"8": "<p>Now Deborah, Rebekah&#8217;s nurse, died and was buried under the oak below Bethel, so it was called Allon Bakuth &#8212; &#8220;Allon Bakuth&#8221; means &#8220;oak of weeping.&#8221; Deborah&#8217;s death &#8212; the nurse who had accompanied Rebekah from her father&#8217;s house (24:59) &#8212; is the death of a faithful servant who had followed the covenant family throughout. The death of the faithful servant at the place of worship is a small detail that Genesis records with care: the names of the faithful dead are preserved even when history would overlook them. Christ preserves the names of the seemingly insignificant: &#8220;I know my sheep and my sheep know me&#8221; (John 10:14); the sparrow that &#8220;will not fall to the ground apart from your Father&#8221; (Matt 10:29). The God who remembers Deborah the nurse is the God who remembers every name.</p>",
"9": "<p>After Jacob returned from Paddan Aram, God appeared to him again and blessed him &#8212; the divine appearance and blessing at Bethel, the second time (the first was the ch28 dream). The God who appears again after the long absence &#8212; who renews the encounter at the place of first encounter &#8212; is the God of persistent covenant: &#8220;The steadfast love of the LORD never ceases; his mercies never come to an end; they are new every morning&#8221; (Lam 3:22&#8211;23). Christ promises the renewed encounter: &#8220;I will see you again and you will rejoice&#8221; (John 16:22). The God who appeared to Jacob at Bethel in ch28 and appears again in ch35 is the God who appeared to the disciples at Easter and promises to appear again at the Second Coming.</p>",
"10": "<p>God said to him, &#8220;Your name is Jacob, but you will no longer be called Jacob; your name will be Israel.&#8221; So he named him Israel &#8212; the second conferral of the name Israel (first at Peniel, 32:28). The name change marks the new identity that God gives: the supplanter (Jacob) becomes the one who struggles with God and prevails (Israel). The divine giving of a new name is the type of the new identity that Christ gives: &#8220;To the one who is victorious, I will give&#8230; a white stone with a new name written on it, known only to the one who receives it&#8221; (Rev 2:17). The new name given by God &#8212; not by human achievement but by divine encounter &#8212; is the permanent, unalterable identity of those who belong to him. Christ gives his people their truest name: &#8220;children of God&#8221; (John 1:12; 1 John 3:1).</p>",
"11": "<p>God said, &#8220;I am God Almighty; be fruitful and increase in number. A nation and a community of nations will come from you, and kings will come from your body&#8221; &#8212; El Shaddai (God Almighty) &#8212; the name revealed to Abraham in 17:1 &#8212; now given to Jacob at Bethel. The covenant renewed with the fullness of the Abrahamic formula: fruitfulness, nations, and kings. The &#8220;kings&#8221; who will come from Jacob&#8217;s body runs through David to the one who is &#8220;King of kings and Lord of lords&#8221; (Rev 19:16). The &#8220;community of nations&#8221; (qahal goyim) anticipates the Gentile nations included in the covenant community through Christ: &#8220;I will also make you a light for the Gentiles, that my salvation may reach to the ends of the earth&#8221; (Isa 49:6; Acts 13:47). El Shaddai&#8217;s covenant runs from Jacob through David to Christ.</p>",
"12": "<p>&#8220;The land I gave to Abraham and Isaac I also give to you, and I will give this land to your descendants after you&#8221; &#8212; the land promise renewed to Jacob at Bethel. The threefold chain of covenant land promise &#8212; Abraham, Isaac, Jacob &#8212; is the OT&#8217;s repeated testimony to covenant faithfulness across generations. Stephen recounts this chain (Acts 7:2&#8211;8) as the testimony of God&#8217;s keeping of promises even when human failure might have broken them. The ultimate land promise is the new creation: &#8220;Blessed are the meek, for they will inherit the earth&#8221; (Matt 5:5). The land that God promises to Jacob&#8217;s descendants finds its fullest expression in the new heaven and new earth (Rev 21:1&#8211;3) that Christ opens as the ultimate covenant land.</p>",
"13": "<p>Then God went up from him at the place where he had talked with him &#8212; the divine ascent after the Bethel theophany. The God who descends to speak and then ascends &#8212; the pattern of divine visitation followed by departure &#8212; is the type of the incarnation&#8217;s structure: &#8220;I came from the Father and entered the world; now I am leaving the world and going back to the Father&#8221; (John 16:28). The ascension of Christ after his resurrection-appearances follows exactly this pattern: he appeared, spoke, blessed &#8212; and then &#8220;was taken up before their very eyes, and a cloud hid him from their sight&#8221; (Acts 1:9). The &#8220;God went up&#8221; at Bethel is the type of the ascension that completes the incarnation&#8217;s journey.</p>",
"14": "<p>Jacob set up a stone pillar at the place where God had talked with him, and he poured out a drink offering on it; he also poured oil on it &#8212; the memorial pillar with drink offering and oil. The combination of the stone pillar (memorial of divine encounter), the anointing oil (the royal/priestly anointing), and the drink offering (the libation of covenant sacrifice) is a pre-Mosaic form of worship that anticipates the Mosaic sacrificial system. The oil poured over the stone is the type of the Spirit poured on Christ: &#8220;God anointed Jesus of Nazareth with the Holy Spirit and power&#8221; (Acts 10:38); &#8220;you have anointed him with the oil of joy&#8221; (Heb 1:9, citing Ps 45:7). The anointed stone at Bethel is the type of the Anointed One &#8212; the Messiah/Christ.</p>",
"15": "<p>Jacob called the place where God had talked with him Bethel &#8212; the naming is the second confirmation of the name Bethel (the first was in 28:19). The repeated naming of the place &#8212; this is &#8220;house of God&#8221; &#8212; is the covenant community&#8217;s way of marking sacred geography: the places where God has spoken are named and remembered. Christ redefines sacred geography: &#8220;a time is coming when you will worship the Father neither on this mountain nor in Jerusalem&#8221; (John 4:21). The place of encounter with God is no longer a geographical location (Bethel, Jerusalem) but a person: &#8220;I am the way and the truth and the life. No one comes to the Father except through me&#8221; (John 14:6). Christ is the true Bethel &#8212; the house of God &#8212; in whom God and humanity meet.</p>",
"16": "<p>Then they moved on from Bethel. While they were still some distance from Ephrath, Rachel began to give birth and had great difficulty &#8212; Rachel&#8217;s labor begins in the interval between Bethel and Ephrath. The geography of the narrative places Rachel&#8217;s death between the covenant renewal (Bethel) and the burial place near Bethlehem. The painful labor between the place of blessing and the place of burial is the type of the &#8220;already and not yet&#8221; of the covenant community&#8217;s experience: the blessing has been renewed but the suffering continues on the way. Paul describes this: &#8220;We ourselves, who have the firstfruits of the Spirit, groan inwardly as we wait eagerly for our adoption to sonship, the redemption of our bodies&#8221; (Rom 8:23). The covenant community groans between Bethel and Bethlehem.</p>",
"17": "<p>As she was having great difficulty, the midwife said to her, &#8220;Don&#8217;t despair, for you have another son&#8221; &#8212; &#8220;don&#8217;t despair&#8221; in the moment of greatest pain: the midwife&#8217;s comfort to the dying Rachel. The comfort offered in the moment of death by the announcement of new life &#8212; &#8220;you have a son!&#8221; &#8212; is the type of the gospel&#8217;s comfort to those facing death: &#8220;Do not let your hearts be troubled&#8230; I am going there to prepare a place for you&#8221; (John 14:1&#8211;2). Christ addresses the &#8220;don&#8217;t despair&#8221; to the dying in the ultimate sense: &#8220;I am the resurrection and the life. The one who believes in me will live, even though they die&#8221; (John 11:25). The midwife&#8217;s comfort is the type of the one who stands at the side of the dying and promises life.</p>",
"18": "<p>As she breathed her last, she named him Ben-Oni. But his father named him Benjamin &#8212; Ben-Oni = &#8220;son of my sorrow/pain&#8221; (the mother&#8217;s dying name); Benjamin = &#8220;son of the right hand&#8221; (the father&#8217;s renaming). The dying mother names her son for her pain; the living father renames him for honor. The transformation from &#8220;son of sorrow&#8221; to &#8220;son of the right hand&#8221; is one of the OT&#8217;s clearest types of the resurrection reversal. Christ is &#8220;a man of sorrows and acquainted with grief&#8221; (Isa 53:3) &#8212; Ben-Oni &#8212; who is raised and exalted to &#8220;the right hand of the Majesty in heaven&#8221; (Heb 1:3; 8:1) &#8212; Benjamin. The Psalm 110:1 promise (&#8220;Sit at my right hand&#8221;) is the divine renaming from Ben-Oni to Benjamin. The one born through sorrow becomes the one seated at the right hand of God.</p>",
"19": "<p>So Rachel died and was buried on the way to Ephrath (that is, Bethlehem) &#8212; Rachel&#8217;s death and burial at Bethlehem. Jeremiah 31:15: &#8220;A voice is heard in Ramah, mourning and great weeping, Rachel weeping for her children and refusing to be comforted, because they are no more.&#8221; Matthew 2:18 applies this to Herod&#8217;s massacre of the infants at Bethlehem: the ancient weeping at Rachel&#8217;s tomb (near Bethlehem) is the type of the weeping at Christ&#8217;s birth. The Messiah is born at Bethlehem &#8212; the place of Rachel&#8217;s tomb &#8212; in the midst of weeping. The birth of the one who will ultimately end all weeping (Rev 21:4: &#8220;He will wipe every tear from their eyes&#8221;) is accompanied by the tears of Rachel. The place of Rachel&#8217;s death becomes the place of the world&#8217;s salvation.</p>",
"20": "<p>Over her tomb Jacob set up a pillar, and to this day that pillar marks Rachel&#8217;s tomb &#8212; the memorial pillar over Rachel&#8217;s grave. The tomb marked with a pillar &#8212; the memorial stone over the place of death &#8212; is the type of all the tomb-stones that mark where death has been. The stone over the tomb: Joseph&#8217;s brothers&#8217; pit; the great stone over the door of the well in ch29; the stone over Jesus&#8217;s tomb (Matt 27:60). The stone that marks the place of death is rolled away at the resurrection (Matt 28:2). Rachel&#8217;s tomb-pillar stands as a permanent marker of death; Christ&#8217;s rolled-away stone stands as the permanent marker of death&#8217;s defeat. The two stones tell the two halves of the gospel story: death is real, and death is undone.</p>",
"21": "<p>Israel moved on again and pitched his tent beyond Migdal Eder &#8212; Migdal Eder means &#8220;tower of the flock/herd.&#8221; Jewish tradition (Targum Pseudo-Jonathan) identifies Migdal Eder as the watchtower near Bethlehem from which the shepherds watched over the temple-bound flocks &#8212; and therefore the traditional location of the angelic announcement to the shepherds at Christ&#8217;s birth (Luke 2:8&#8211;20). The covenant-bearer pitching his tent &#8220;beyond the tower of the flock&#8221; near Bethlehem connects this geography to the shepherds who will keep watch at the same tower when the true Lamb of God is born. Israel&#8217;s tent at Migdal Eder near Bethlehem prefigures the angelic announcement to the shepherds in the same fields.</p>",
"22": "<p>While Israel was living in that region, Reuben went in and slept with his father&#8217;s concubine Bilhah, and Israel heard of it &#8212; Reuben&#8217;s sin with Bilhah violates the father&#8217;s household. The firstborn&#8217;s sin that costs him the birthright (49:3&#8211;4: &#8220;you will no longer excel, for you went up onto your father&#8217;s bed&#8221;) is the type of the failure of the natural firstborn. The birthright that Reuben forfeits by his sin &#8212; like Esau&#8217;s despising of the birthright (25:34) &#8212; is consistently passed to a later son. The &#8220;natural&#8221; firstborn who forfeits is the type of the old covenant&#8217;s failure; the one who receives the birthright by divine grace rather than birth-order is the type of the new covenant&#8217;s promise. Christ is the true firstborn (Col 1:15; Heb 12:23) who does not forfeit but perfectly fulfills his birthright.</p>",
"23": "<p>The sons of Leah: Reuben the firstborn of Jacob, Simeon, Levi, Judah, Issachar and Zebulun &#8212; the enumeration of Leah&#8217;s six sons begins the formal tribal list. The formal listing of the twelve tribes is the covenant family&#8217;s genealogical identity. Christ reconstitutes the twelve explicitly: twelve apostles corresponding to twelve tribes (Matt 10:1&#8211;4; 19:28: &#8220;you who have followed me will also sit on twelve thrones, judging the twelve tribes of Israel&#8221;). The twelve tribes of the OT and the twelve apostles of the NT are both grounded in the covenant purposes of God that run from Jacob through Christ. The formal enumeration begun here will be fulfilled in the New Jerusalem where both twelves are inscribed: the twelve gates (tribes) and twelve foundations (apostles) of Rev 21:12&#8211;14.</p>",
"24": "<p>The sons of Rachel: Joseph and Benjamin &#8212; Rachel&#8217;s two sons &#8212; only two compared to Leah&#8217;s six, the beloved wife who struggled with barrenness and died in childbirth. Joseph (the greatest OT type of Christ) and Benjamin (&#8220;son of the right hand&#8221;, the Christ-at-ascension type) are the two sons who come through the most suffering and the most love. The covenant family&#8217;s most Christ-typological sons come through the most beloved wife who suffered most. The pattern of the greatest gifts coming through the deepest suffering runs through both Genesis and the gospel: &#8220;Was it not necessary that the Christ should suffer these things and enter into his glory?&#8221; (Luke 24:26). Joseph and Benjamin &#8212; the greatest type and the &#8220;right hand&#8221; name &#8212; are Rachel&#8217;s gift to the covenant through her suffering.</p>",
"25": "<p>The sons of Rachel&#8217;s servant Bilhah: Dan and Naphtali &#8212; the two surrogate sons through Bilhah are included in the tribal enumeration without distinction. The formal equality of the twelve in the tribal list &#8212; regardless of whether born of wife or servant &#8212; is the type of the covenant community&#8217;s inclusivity: &#8220;There is neither Jew nor Gentile, neither slave nor free&#8221; (Gal 3:28). The covenant community does not stratify its members by origin; all twelve tribes are equally Israel. The gospel&#8217;s radical inclusion of those from every background into the covenant family is already anticipated in the way the twelve are enumerated: the sons of the servants alongside the sons of the wives, all equally &#8220;the sons of Jacob.&#8221;</p>",
"26": "<p>The sons of Leah&#8217;s servant Zilpah: Gad and Asher. These were the sons of Jacob, born to him in Paddan Aram &#8212; the enumeration of all twelve sons is now complete. The summary &#8220;these were the sons of Jacob&#8221; encompasses all twelve regardless of mother or circumstance of birth &#8212; the covenant paternity overrides the biological complexity. The covenant Father who names all his children as his own: &#8220;Yet to all who did receive him, to those who believed in his name, he gave the right to become children of God &#8212; children born not of natural descent, nor of human decision or a husband&#8217;s will, but born of God&#8221; (John 1:12&#8211;13). The covenant family&#8217;s membership is defined by the Father&#8217;s naming, not by the conditions of birth. &#8220;These were the sons of Jacob&#8221; &#8212; and &#8220;these are the children of God&#8221; (Rom 8:16).</p>",
"27": "<p>Jacob came home to his father Isaac in Mamre, near Kiriath Arba (that is, Hebron), where Abraham and Isaac had stayed &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s return to his father Isaac at Mamre/Hebron &#8212; the place where Abraham dwelt and where the patriarchal burial cave at Machpelah is located (23:17&#8211;20). The homecoming of the son to the father after the long journey &#8212; Jacob returns to Isaac after 20+ years of absence. The prodigal son returns home: &#8220;I will set out and go back to my father&#8221; (Luke 15:18). The homecoming to the father&#8217;s house at Hebron &#8212; the place of the covenant dead &#8212; is the type of the ultimate homecoming to the Father. Christ prepares the homecoming: &#8220;I am going to prepare a place for you&#8230; that you also may be where I am&#8221; (John 14:2&#8211;3).</p>",
"28": "<p>Isaac lived a hundred and eighty years &#8212; Isaac&#8217;s lifespan recorded. The patriarchal life-summary &#8212; the length of days given to the covenant-bearer &#8212; is Genesis&#8217;s way of honoring the completed life. Isaac&#8217;s 180 years is fewer than Abraham&#8217;s 175 (25:7) &#8212; the decreasing lifespans that reflect the post-flood narrowing. The length of a life is the gift of God: &#8220;all the days ordained for me were written in your book before one of them came to be&#8221; (Ps 139:16). Christ&#8217;s life on earth was 33 years &#8212; not long by patriarchal standards &#8212; but complete: &#8220;I have brought you glory on earth by finishing the work you gave me to do&#8221; (John 17:4). The completeness of a life is not measured by its length but by its faithfulness to the divine calling.</p>",
"29": "<p>Then he breathed his last and died and was gathered to his people, old and full of years. And his sons Esau and Jacob buried him &#8212; Isaac&#8217;s death and burial by the reconciled brothers Esau and Jacob together. The reconciled sons burying their father together is the image of covenant peace: the brothers who had been estranged &#8212; the deceptive covenant-bearer and the wronged Esau &#8212; stand together at their father&#8217;s grave. Paul&#8217;s vision of the gospel: &#8220;through him to reconcile to himself all things&#8230; by making peace through his blood, shed on the cross&#8221; (Col 1:20). The reconciliation of Esau and Jacob that ch33 began reaches its visible expression here: the two brothers standing together, united in honoring their covenant father. This is the type of the eschatological reconciliation that Christ achieves &#8212; the unity of all things under the one Father, in the one Son.</p>",
},
}

